3 - Aesthetic mappings

3.1 - Notes

Aesthetic mapping lets you highlight specific components of the data. Aesthetics includes things like size, shape and color. One can use aesthetic mapping like this.

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, color = class))

Here is the same example, using size instead.

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, size = class))

This gives us a different aesthetic, however, in this case it is not advised as it is very difficult to differentiate different groups based on size. Other things we can map includes: alpha (transparency) and shape.

Furthermore, we can set aesthetics manually like this.

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy), color = "blue")

Notice that the color is outside of the x and y parentheses, but still inside the aes.

You can look up information on the types of shapes that are available in R. There is a total of 25.

4 - Facets

4.1 - Notes

One additional way to show your data is to split your plot into subplots, also called facets. Facets can be created using the facet_wrap() function. To pass a variable to facet_wrap() you need to cast a variable with a formula (~).

This can be done line this:

ggplot(data = mpg) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) +
  facet_wrap(~ class, nrow = 1)

It is also possible to facet a plot in combination with two variables using facet_grid(). This function creates a x and y axis, sort of like a heatmap.

ggplot(data = mpg) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) +
  facet_grid(drv ~ class)

It is apparantly possible to make a facet_grid() into a facet_wrap(nrow = 1) by writing e.g., facet_grid(. ~ cyl). I do however not see why would do this instead of a facet wrap. I would argue that a wrap is more readable.

Question 4 - Take this faceted plot. What are the advantages and disadvantages of using faceting instead of color aesthetic?

ggplot(data = mpg) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) +
  facet_wrap(~ class, nrow = 2)

Answer:

Advantages

  • You split up your view. Make it simpler if you have a larger dataset.

  • If you have many variables to show, it can be difficult to see differences in shapes and colour.

  • If the cases are somehow independent of each other.

Disadvantages

  • If you just have a small dataset, it can seem empty.

  • Difficult to compare direct values.

5 - Geometric Objects

5.1 - Notes

You make different plots/graphs in R by using different geoms (geometric object). These can include:

  • geom_point = scatter plot
ggplot(data = mpg) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy))
  • geom_smooth = line graph
ggplot(data = mpg) +
  geom_smooth(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy))

While all geoms takes mapping functions, they cant always contain the same type of asthetics. For example, a line graph can not contain shapes or different colors. However, for line graphs you can for example set the linetype like this:

ggplot(data = mpg) +
  geom_smooth(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, linetype = drv))

Here the function separates the car dependent on the drivetrain type (drv). We can also do this, and add points to the graph to make it clearer, containing two geoms in the same graph, like this.

ggplot(data = mpg) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) +
  geom_smooth(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, linetype = drv))

The problem here is however that you essentially write the code two times. An alternative is to write code like this:

ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = displ, y= hwy)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color =class)) +
  geom_smooth(mapping = aes(linetype = drv))

Here you can also see that it is possible to place mapping functions inside only one geom and filter data, showing only some of it.

6 - Statistical Transformation

6.1 - Notes

Some plots automatically calculate new values for your plots. An example is the diamonds data set where there is no count variable. When making a bar plot a count is calculated:

When doing this, the plots bins the data, and counts the number/count that falls within each bin. This occurs for bar charts, histograms, and frequency polygons.

Other automatically calculated stuff can include smoothness model, and summary from boxplots.

The algorithms used for these transformations are called a stat (short for statistical transformation).

You can see/view which stat that geoms uses by using ?.

?geom_bar

Here it says:

geom_bar() uses stat_count() by default.

You can sometimes use stats interchangeability with geoms. The previous graph can also be made like this.

ggplot(data = diamonds) +
  stat_count(mapping = aes(x = cut))

There are three reasons you might choose to use stats over geoms.

  1. Override default stat (i.e.change from count to identity)
demo <- tribble (
  ~a,       ~b,
  "bar_1",  20,
  "bar_2",  30,
  "bar_3",  40,
)

ggplot(data = demo) +
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = a, y = b), stat = "identity")

  1. Override default mapping. You might want to show something other than a normal Y column, for example proportion.
ggplot(data = diamonds) +
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = cut, y = ..prop.., group = 1))

  1. You can add more summary data to the plot.
ggplot(data = diamonds) +
  stat_summary(mapping = aes(x = cut, y = depth), fun.min = min, fun.max = max, fun = median)

2 - What does geom_col() do? How is it different to geom_bar()?

Lets find out.

?geom_col()

Geom_bar makes the height of the bar proportional to number of cases in each group. If you want them to be reperesent values in the acctual data, geom_col() does this. I.e. geom_bar() uses stat_count, while geom_col() uses stat_identity.

3 - Most geoms and stats come in pairs that are almost always used in concert. What does these pairs have in common?

We should read documentation.

?stat_bin()

They often have similar names. They often do the same thing. Also, they use each other for the same thing. I.e. geom uses a stat, and a stat shows it using a geom. Dont really know why there are two types. Maybe to make it easier in edgecases.

4 - What variables does stat_smooth() compute? What parameter controls its behavior?

?stat_smooth()

Stat smooth compute the SE using the predictdf function (usually). Also, y, ymin, and yma. The parameters that controls its behavior is method, formula, and na.rm.

7 - Position Adjustments

7.1 - Notes

You can fill bar charts using the color aesthetic.

ggplot(data = diamonds) +
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = cut, color = cut))

Or better yet

ggplot(data = diamonds) +
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = cut, fill = cut))

You can also fill stuff in different variables like this:

ggplot(data = diamonds) +
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = cut, fill = clarity))

You can use position function to set how the different colors should be positioned. In the below example they are positioned based on their identity.

ggplot(data = diamonds, mapping = aes(x = cut, fill = clarity)) +
  geom_bar(alpha = 1/5, position = "identity")

Alpha stand for ocupizaty.

You can also set a fill position

ggplot(data = diamonds, mapping = aes(x = cut, fill = clarity)) +
  geom_bar(position = "fill")

Here we fill the entire Y axis. This makes it easier to compare propoprtions of clarity inside the same sample.

Lastly we can use the dodge function to make objects overlap.

ggplot(data = diamonds, mapping = aes(x = cut, fill = clarity)) +
  geom_bar(alpha = 1/5, position = "dodge")

There are also more types of adjustements that are more useful for other types of geoms. For example, if points overlap (called overplotting) you can avoid this by using the jitter function. This function adds some random noise to each variable so that you are able to see them all.

This would in theory make your graph less accurate at small scales, however, more accurate at large scales.

YOu can also use geom_jitter() to do this quickly.

Like this:

ggplot(data = mpg) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy), position = "jitter")

8 - Coordinate systems

8.1 - Notes

Coordinate systems are the most complicated part of ggplot2. The default coordinate system is something called cartesian coordinate. This is where x and y is independent. There is also a bunh of other stuff that is usefull

  • Coord_flip = Switches x and y axis.
ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = class, y = hwy)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  coord_flip()
  • coord quickmap = Sets aspect ratio correctly for maps (spartial data).
install.packages("maps")
nz <- map_data("nz")

ggplot(data = nz, aes(long, lat, group = group)) +
  geom_polygon(fill = "white", color = "black")
  coord_map()
  • Coords_polar = makes polar coordinate.
bar <- ggplot(data = diamonds) +
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = cut, fill = cut), show.legend = FALSE, width = 1) +
  theme(aspect.ratio = 1) +
  labs(x = NULL, y = NULL)

bar + coord_flip()
bar + coord_polar()

9 - The layered grammer of graphics

9.1 - Notes

ggplot template:

ggplot(date = <DATA>) +
  <GEOM>(mapping = aes(<MAPPINGS>), stat = <STAT>, position = <POSITION>) +
  <CORDINATE_FUNCTION> +
